				From what I am reading, there is more to it than simple drivers. Id and Nvidia are saying they worked very closely, and that the new Nvidia GPU's were designed with this engine and DX9 in mind. I could care less either way, their fighting tranlates to eye candy heaven for us! I used to be all about Nvidia as they knocked 3dFX right the fuck off their pedestal. Then ATI, one of the oldest graphics chip makers, somehow comes back from the depths of obsoleteness to give us some of the best and fastest advancements we have seen in ages. Good Lord, does anyone here remember the first "3D Polygon" games? Virtua Fighter comes to mind. I can remember being extrememly dissapointed at the time as I was so used to "sprites". The poly characters had no detail or depth compared to their pixelated siblings. I am a believer now!!!! In the same realm, Alienware is coming out with dual CPU, dual GPU machines this year. NICE! And if you really want to hit the high end. GO over and look at these boxes. I dare anyone here to find me a better system.... reasonable, don't come back at me with a freaking SGI box, or BigBlue.. ;-) These things have a 16gb ramdisk, just for starters, that runs at somewhere around 8gb/s if I remember correctly. Combine it with their custom WINXP and a 4 panel 90inch lcd monitor, and your about to vomit just looking at it....<br /><br />http://www.go-l.com<br /><br />My wish for the near future is independent goggles. What I mean by that is goggles that are NOT a controller, but also more than mere "3D" shutter glasses. I want to be able to play a flight sim and look around outside the cockpit independently from the steering of the craft. Or when I am playing Madden, go out for a catch and be able to look over my shoulder for the pass while still running toward the endzone. Or when driving... oh, you got the point? My bad.. LOL... It bugs me they haven't done it yet, it would just be a matter of mapping to the hat...right?<br /><br />Your machine should run Doom without a problem. I am running mine @800x600. I would suggest turning off the AA. With AA off there is not much noticeable difference, while you will get the jaggies on some edges, I have noticed virtually no tearing. There were some settings that had some problems on the non DX9 cards. I do not think the GeForce4 was a DX9 card, but I am not positive on that. I jumped from a 3 to the 5200. I do remember though that those cards were no different in the TI and Ultra models, but for the Bios. You can find Bios upgrades on the net and "unlock" your TI so to speak if you felt so inclined.<br /><br />On a different game.. Has anyone here played Alias on PC? WHAT A CRAPPER OF A GAME!!!! I think they ported it over from XBox and didn't bother to do anything about the controls. Using the keyboard and mouse bites ass, and personally, I will take my keyboard and mouse setup over a gamepad any day. Well for most games. I go with a gamepad on my sports games, and I have a flight stick, and a wheel/pedals for my other games.<br /><br />I have issues!<br />
