			<div class="blogComment">
				<a name="109209035544861269"></a> 
				I just have to slip this in while I am at it... So sorry Mac users but my PC will hang with the Macs any day in the realm they bragged of owning for so long. Graphics, sound, and multimedia production. As far as I am concerned, Steve Jobs should be taken to the desert and quartered for squandering Apple Computers. I used to be a big Apple fan. I learned programming back in the day using Pascal on a IIc. He has tried to run this company like it is a freaking head shop catering to niche users. PROPRIETARY will spell the doom of any piece of equipment, and he has succeeded with great expertise at reminding us all of that point. Even when he switched to the PCI bus years back, in an attempt to make MACs more compatable, he used a proprietary version, unlike the IBM/Intel boxes 99% of the rest of the world uses. As I said in my last post about the 3DFX/Nvidia/ATI war... we the users benefit from their competition. <br /><br />I am reminded of a little fight in the late 80's between IBM and the rest of the PC market. If anyone remembers the IBM PS1 & PS2, they might remember something called the Microchannel Architecture or MCA Bus. IBM built it as the successor to the ISA Bus. Well about the same time, the PCI Bus was also released by the group that comes up with standards for equipment, I can't remember what they are called, but they are the people who define things like CAT5, VGA plugs, etc. Anyway, they agreed on the PCI standard. The MCA was way ahead of the PCI in performance, so much so that my little 286 MCA box was running circles around the 486's, and even some Pentiums my buddies had. I was even running the all new King of OS's, WIN 95! ;-) God that makes me feel old. Anyway, a 286 was not supposed to be able to run 95. My machine was winning in almost every benchmark we tried. So IBM had built a much better mousetrap. They were so sure of themselves and that the world would coming foaming at the mouth for it that they failed to heed a very valuable lesson from Sony and the much more superior format BetaMax that we had all seen only ten years earlier. IBM decided to charge everyone a per unit surcharge to put MCA slots in their boxes... Okay, let me see.... Free PCI.... surcharged MCA.... Who won? How many people have even heard of MCA now? <br /><br />This is also the lesson that Steve Jobs unfortunately cannot seem to heed. Apple has been so close to death so many times now it is rediculous. If you all remember it was Bill Gates himself that GAVE Jobs a wad of millions about 12 years ago so that Apple didn't fold, and cause him more headaches on the monopoly front. It was simply more profitable for Microsoft to prop them up. What does that say about the management skills of Jobs? Anyway, what used to be the creme of the crop when it came to graphic art and music production is becoming more and more every day, a boutique computer that will become a footnote of names like Amiga(which Jobs also bought and tanked), Commodore, and the Atari 400/800. Which in all honesty is truly sad. <br /><br />So what does the flower child computer genius get himself into these days? Well his latest endeavor with the Ipod and Itunes takes him into his 3rd lawsuit with the Beatles, one which the Beatles are unlikely to back down from or settle out of court this go around, as Apple is not just flirting on the edges of the music business, they are up to their neck in it. Clearly in violation of copywrite and trademark laws. Jobs has been able to finesse over the Beatles and Apple Records by staying along the edges of music, the outcome of this will more than likely be a huge punitive sum to Apple Records, and the name Apple Computer will probably be replaced by Macintosh Computer, which if Jobs had an ounce of a brain, he would have done ten years ago as most people identify with the MAC name quicker than the Apple Computer name anyway... Can anyone here tell me this guy isn't an idiot?<br /><br />Actually, that may not work either. There is a high end audio equipment company called Mcintosh that has been around nearly a century. They make some incredible equipment, if you ever get a chance to hear it, take a listen.. <br /><br />Now taking suggestions for a new name for Apple.... Any ideas?<br />
